			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"><span style="font-style: italic"><span style="font-weight: bold">~III~</span></span>
<br />

<br />

<br />
It had been yet another uneventful day. Not that that was a bad thing. I had been trudging through the dense woods all day. I didn’t like traveling through the daylight but I’m pressed for time and feel relatively hidden in the forest. Most Therali skirted around these woods in their travels. It’s easy to understand why.
<br />
	
<br />
Trees, packed tightly together, rose like towers, their thick foliage blocking out the sun. Aside from a few rays sneaking through cracks in the leaves here and there the forest was engulfed in a greenish gloom. While the shade offered relief from the searing heat of the sun the enclosure increased the humidity and mustiness. The horrible terrain and poor air quality mixed with my physical exertion forced me to rest more than I would have liked.
<br />
	
<br />
Sitting at the edge of the tree line and peering out into the barren landscape that lay ahead my thoughts come creeping in again. The stench of death filled the air here. This site holds a gruesome past. It’s almost as if the land itself hasn’t aged at all since that time. It’s been 21 years but the ground remains torn up. Cracked boulders, patches of dried grass, and dead, broken trees lay strewn about. Ripped clothing, rusted weapons, and skeletal remains can still be found.
<br />
	
<br />
I try to look away. It would take a full day’s ride to reach the Southern Wastes from here. They would be expecting my arrival. The Advys Mortifera would have been keeping tabs on my whereabouts. There was no time waste. But my mind kept drifting to memories of the horror I’d experienced here so many years ago.
<br />
	
<br />
This was the site of the darkest day in Unali history. I suppose I should start from the beginning. All the races of Ondrikoth believed in an afterlife. That is where the religious similarities end though. The Therali, Etokin, and Subterrans, all believe in a supreme ruler. However, neither of them believes in the same god. We Unali did not believe in any god. 
<br />
	
<br />
Every living creature, be it a person, animal, or plant, has a life force. Life can be given and life can be taken away but the pool of energy is a constant. A tree is born and a portion of energy is drained from the pool. A wolf dies and energy is returned to the pool. This cycle, and pool, of life energy is not governed by any supreme being.
<br />
	
<br />
As Unali, we devoted our lives to the study of this force. The other races did not approve of our meddling with matters that should be left up to their respective gods. They worried that we would bring doom upon all living creatures, that we would anger the gods. 
<br />
	
<br />
You can only imagine their horror when we finally learned how to tap this power. They were outraged. We were labeled devil worshippers, cast out of acceptance. The other races chose to deal with us in their own special ways.
<br />
	
<br />
The Subterrans did not approve but took a position of indifference. We’d had no dealings with them before so there was really no change. They believed we would be the source of our own destruction and so needed not interfere.
<br />
	
<br />
The Etokin chose to shun us completely. They cut all trade ties with us and quite simply went about life as if we did not, and never did, exist.
<br />
	
<br />
The Therali took a more violent approach. We shared a continent with them, and they were not happy with that. King Rheon proclaimed us heretics. He massed armies against us as his way of eradicating the evil that plagued his land. He would not relent until his vision of genocide was complete.
<br />
	
<br />
Thus began the Rheonic Wars. Both sides would suffer heavy losses in bloody battles that raged over the following 17 years. Our villages were destroyed. We were hunted like animals. But we would not yield. We had armies of our own. What we lacked in numbers we made up for in magical superiority.
<br />
	
<br />
It was only a matter of time, however, before our reserves were depleted. The Therali numbered in the millions. We could not overcome a force of that size. We held our ground, here, in this field.
<br />
	
<br />
