				<td valign="top" align="right" nowrap="nowrap"><a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=1569&amp;sid=c4b7339064ad42ef766779fc0d4c8919"><img src="templates/myth2/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>   </td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"><span style="font-style: italic">...continued from ^</span>
<br />

<br />

<br />
For nine months we broke wave upon wave that Rheon threw at us. Both sides were exhausted. We could not make headway against Rheon but he also could not rid himself of us. His followers were tiring of the war and were frustrated with his inability to finish us off. It was around this point that the tide turned, against us.
<br />

<br />
A royal envoy from Etokin was slaughtered. The blame was pinned upon us Unali. I still believe to this day, though it has not been proven, that the Therali themselves were behind the murder to draw the Etokin into the war.
<br />

<br />
Elinoi dispatched their own forces and for the first time in the history of Ondrikoth, the Etokin and Therali fought as allies. We never had a chance. They drove our forces into what has henceforth been known as the Valley of Ash.  They slaughtered so many, even their own people, with the hellfire they set that day.
<br />

<br />
I can still remember the screams and smell of burnt flesh as if it were just yesterday.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-size: 18px; line-height: normal"><span style="font-weight: bold">…</span></span>
<br />
		
<br />
A seemingly endless parade of hail crashed down upon us. Recyn stood to my right trying to talk to me. I couldn’t hear him over the thunder of the hail ringing off thousands of armored bodies. I shrug as he stares at me. He just laughs and looks back out into the fog that has enshrouded us.
<br />
	
<br />
We can’t see more than a few feet in any direction. That may be a good thing. Who truly wants to see their death coming? I had no doubt that this man made weather would be cleared up before long. This magical storm was the work of a high rank druid, most likely an Etokin one. One of the divisions of our forces was no doubt handling that problem at the moment.
<br />
	
<br />
I’ve been feeling vibrations in the ground and they’ve gotten quite strong. That’s not the weather. More like the approaching armies come to destroy us. They would be upon us soon. Recyn touches my shoulder and I realize I’ve been holding my breath. He nods grimly. I nod back, knowing the time is near. No matter how many times you face death it never gets easier.
<br />
	
<br />
Then the wind is gone. Just like that. The hail now falls straight and I can see a little better. I can now see dark figures not a stone’s throw away. There are so many. Beside me Recyn draws his sword. I favor the lighter one handed sword but he wields a massive two hander. His body size is nearly twice that of mine and I’m by no means small. His eyes, so dark, appear focused on something that only he can see.
<br />
	
<br />
As I unsheathe my sword a few orange rays of light glint off the blade. I look up to see the distorted glow through the dissipating fog. “I told you it’d clear up Drei. There’s the sun to shine upon us as we prepare to smite our foes.” He says still gazing ahead at the undistinguishable shapes in the distance.
<br />
	
<br />
A sharp whine pierces the air. The rays brighten and I feel a building of heat in the air. Looking up the glow is bigger, closer. “Recyn, that’s not the sun.” I say, fear starting to tear at my heart.
<br />
	
<br />
The whine is replaced by screams as the fireball crashes into the crowd.
<br />
 
<br />
<span style="font-size: 18px; line-height: normal"><span style="font-weight: bold">...</span></span>
<br />

<br />
I come out of my daydream; the sun is shining in my eyes as it sets over the wasteland before me. It’s time to get going. Making sure it’s clear I step out of the protection of the tree line to search for the components I need to reanimate my means of travel.
<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">Continued...</span></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
